<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Consumer Futures (HOT49)</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our response to this question focuses on domestic heat energy demand from existing homes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We consider that there is considerable room for improvement in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">current approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to heat energy demand reduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Deal is an incomplete offer for consumers, who are yet to be ‘sold’ the benefits of energy efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This lack </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of desirability increases the cost of delivering ECO, adding to the costs on consumers’ energy bills</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Deal and the ECO will fail to deliver the Government’s carbon and fuel poverty goals</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This failure could be exacerbated if Government does not use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> carbon taxation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the capacity mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to support energy efficiency improvements</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consumer Futures is a strong supporter of ‘fabric first’. New heat technologies such as heat pumps should only be installed when a property’s heat demand is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">minimised, to reduce both installation cost (through correct sizing) and running c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ost. At present it appears the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of a heat pump system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cannot compete with gas central heating and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">neither the financial or environmental case has been made to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people to make that switch.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> barriers to the take-up of heat pumps in a domestic setting will include: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">·</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of consumer familiarity with the technologies and their operation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">·</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">High up-front costs of installation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">·</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disruption associated with installa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">·</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Higher than expected running costs, particularly where properties are poorly insulated</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">·</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reported poor experiences, perhaps related to some of the above</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Community heating is not more common due to the sunk costs in Britain’s gas network and, even </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if this barrier is overcome, we suspect consumers will turn against an option that is unregulated and has no competitive pressures on pricing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thermal storage is useful, but</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is likely to cause confusion for consumers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Space for storage in the home is decre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">asing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, so must be coordinated at the community scale</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government’s energy performance procedure does not recognise the value of interseasonal thermal storage</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">energy demand?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We consider that there is considerable room for improvement in the current approach. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Deal is an incomplete offer for consumers, who are yet to be ‘sold’ the benefits of energy efficiency</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This lack of desirability increases the cost of deliverin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g ECO, adding to the costs on consumers’ energy bills</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Deal and the ECO will fail to deliver the Government’s carbon and fuel poverty goals</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This failure could be addressed by</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> revenue from carbon taxation and the capacity mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to support energy efficiency improvements</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consumer engagement facilitated by</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 136.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A clear vision for the housing stock, with messaging embedded in the property market in the form of information (EPCs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, minimum standards,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and incentives such as a stamp duty reb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 136.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Data sharing to reduce the costs of identifying consumers eligible for support</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 136.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Funding for area-based initiatives</span></li></ul></ol></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Engaging consumers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its current format</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Green Deal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> catalyse the installation of measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at a significant scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the able-to-pay market. Green Deal finance helps overcome the barrier of lack of access to upfront capital, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but this cannot deliver change if consumers do not want the product in the first place</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lthough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a completely new market for consumers a te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tative start is to be expected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the figures on uptake of Green Deal plans and the Green Deal cashback incentives suggest low latent demand for energy demand reduction measures and it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appears that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the current framework is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sufficient to develop a self-su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">staining market for domestic energy efficiency measures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We consider that, stronger, clearer, incentives, such as stamp duty rebate, are needed to encourage consumers to act, as outlined in a recent report by the UK Green Building Council</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More generally, Government should set out a clear vision for the existing housing stock, set targets that give notice to consumers and the property market, be prepared to continuously improve the Green Deal framework by learning from problems as they arise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and provide adequate resources to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inform the public and enforce related regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fuel poor consumers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore needs to be done to support measures for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fuel poor households who cannot afford to improve their home’s energy efficiency. With the move fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om to Green Deal and ECO, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the closure of the publicly funded fuel poverty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme (Warm Front) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government’s own predictions are that the Green Deal and ECO will only help 3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.6 million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> homes, and will fail to meet its carbon and fuel poverty goals.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Energy Company Obligation is expected to lift just 250,000 households out of fuel poverty, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the remainder of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">country’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6 million fuel poor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are unlikely to take up Green Deals due to barriers such as literacy; hassle in the face of po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or health; debt-averseness; or tenure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is one reason why Consumer Futures are supporting the Energy Bill Revolution campaign to provide funds gathered from carbon taxation to support energy efficiency roll-out at the scale needed to seriously tackle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fuel poverty.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Impact on bills</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Compared to CERT, the Energy Company Obligation represents a move to supporting heat demand reduction measures that are less cost-effective, and as such will deliver less demand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduction for the same outlay. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some concern that the costs to consumers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across the life of the programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be higher than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">predicted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lack of desirability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Green Deal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ses the cost of delivering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the carbon sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ving element of ECO. We welcome DECC’s commitm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent to closely monitoring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the costs of the programme, and considering the need for any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anges to the ECO or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> related policies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in light of this evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government should consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all steps it can take to reduce the costs of the programme including, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mong other policies, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extending data-sharing to improve the targeting of the ECO</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, focussing on electrically-heated homes, and supporting area-based schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electrically-heated homes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is significant scope to improve the efficiency of Britain’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">electrically heated homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, an opportunity that must not be lost in the development of the new capacity mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. 2.3 million homes in Britain are heated by electricity (9.3 per cent), including 22 per cent of rural homes in Scotland</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. These households ten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to have a low standard of energy efficiency: only 32 per cent of electric-heated homes in England pass the Decent Homes Standard, compared to 72 per cent of gas-heated homes. It is not clear that Green Deal and ECO will be effective in delivering signifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cant improvements to the energy efficiency of these households, which also pay disproportionately for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the ECO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and other policies</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Reducing heat demand for these households will also reduce the peak electricity demand and the need for costly g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rid and generation reinforcement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Area-based schemes </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommend that the Government considers steps to encourage electricity network companies to help promote heat demand reduction for electricity heated homes, as they have an implicit incentive to m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ake it work in a way that suppliers do not.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Low Carbon Networks Fund now includes energy efficiency as a potential trial project theme but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommend that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> greater emphasis is put on network involvement in this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Looking at best practise from around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the various schemes in the UK, Consumer Futures would like to see more emphasis placed on the detail of the promotion and delivery process of schemes, as well as premium placed on those that can be achieved through an area-based programme, something we re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gard as the most effective route of ensuring cost-effectiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Scottish Government has reported on its approach to reducing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> energy costs and carbon emissions at lowest public sector cost</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This data very clearly shows that area-based programmes whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h provided free based insulation measures were the most successful in the prevailing circumstances. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The approach in Scotland is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> noteworthy for its move away from seeing fuel poverty as a problem which affects a small minority of the populati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on, to an issue which affects around a third of all households in Scotland. This, combined with the success of the Universal Home Insulation Scheme on a measures / pound basis, has led thinking away from narrow targeting towards area-based programmes offer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing a more proportionate response to the problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and allowing for a greater range of engagement techniques</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What progress is the government making on reducing the demand for heat?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment has made some substantial progress on reducing demand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> heat from existing domestic buildings, particularly through the delivery of energy efficiency measures by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">publically funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and supplier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-led programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Under CERT, energy companies achieved estimate savings of 296.9 million lifetime tonnes of carbon diox</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ide (Mt CO2) (against an overall target of 293 Mt CO2), while CESP delivered 16.3Mt CO2 worth of savings (against a target of 19.25 Mt CO2). However there was a lack of transparency and accountability regarding the costs of the schemes and how those costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were recovered from consumers. The final evaluation of the CERT is yet to be completed but Consumer Futures harbours some concerns about the cost effectiveness of these programmes.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e consider that the current policy framework will deliver </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reduct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion in the domestic sector at a slower pace than under the preceding schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not deliver the demand reductions necessary to meet the UK’s fuel poverty and carbon emissions reduction goals. As outlined earli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er, this is because of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the reduction in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support for energy efficiency, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the low priority that energy efficiency has for consumers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consumer Futures does not have the expertise to comment on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainability guidelines but wants the full lifecycle of the biomass to be accounted for; and for guidelines to be continually reviewed as the supply chain develops.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On paper the merits of different heating systems depend on the type of property, particularly its level of insulation, and its location (on or off the gas network). The reality is that a quick</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> search online brings up horror stories of high installation costs, high electricity bills, incorrect installation and cold homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence may be anecdotal but is highly relevant to a consumer considering the relative merits of different heati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng systems.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Costs – running and installation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although we have limited evidence on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how consumers choose their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heating system, the indications are that consumers generally prefer the option of gas central heating if available to them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is mainly a pric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e issue, with mains gas remaining the cheapest form of heat available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and new heating systems carrying a high upfront financial and hassle cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, according to Energy Saving Trust, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the capital costs of insta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">llation are considerable (£6 – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10,000) and running costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at a Coefficient of Performance (CoP) of 1:3 are, at least at present, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> £100 more per year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when compared to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> gas central heating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This does not take into account the support from the Renewable Heat Incentive.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the other hand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the running costs of heat pumps are lower than alternatives in off gas areas, where other options are typically heating oil, electric heating, or LPG. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, the use of heat pumps is only appropriate in well-insulated homes as they run at lower tempera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s than conventional gas heating, and off-gas areas are often rural where there is a higher than average proportion of older, harder-to-treat homes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Without appropriate levels of insulation and easy-to-use controls, consumers are left with cold homes a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd high electricity bills. These issues are exacerbated during colder weather, which reduces the efficiency of heat pumps.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Variance in carbon savings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carbon conversion factors show that the environmental savings from heat pumps depend on the carbon intensity of the electrical input – GB electricity currently has (very close to) three times the carbon impact of mains gas per </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">kWh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. So again, a CoP of 1:3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould currently give minimal, if any, carbon savings compared to mains gas, but would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an improvement on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> heating oil, LPG or direct electric heating.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Grid capacity</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omestic heat pumps can produce a great strain on the elect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ricity grid, and in many cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e unsuitable for providing demand side response. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is in contrast to new-generation storage heate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs, which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offer a more grid-friendly technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with off-peak tariffs,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effective rem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ote switching and greater consumer understanding.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our understanding is that the level of community heating/CHP in the UK has its roots in the UK’s historic infrastructure, cultural issues related to CHP, as well as the growth and prevalence of mains gas as a heating fuel as a result of our natural resourc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This trend may be reversing, however any growth of CHP must be accompanied by strong consumer protection. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Community Heating/CHP is not a regulated industry nor are its consumers able to switch suppliers. The lack of either regulation or competitive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pressure means that consumers can suffer high costs with little alternative, and fuel poor customers of district heating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not enjoying the same protections as equivalent consumers taking electricity and gas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the work of the CHPA to develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a voluntary consumer protection scheme, for which Consumer Futures sits on the steering group. However, it is not clear that a voluntary scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure the level of coverage, and the effective sanctions, required for effective consumer protection. We h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ave particular doubts regarding the effectiveness of a voluntary scheme in protecting consumers on existing heat networks. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling? </span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:105%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government should give a clear signal that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> environmental or fabric cooling measures are preferable to those that use electricity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government should explore the use of high thermal mass to store heat; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it helps keep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> buildings cool in summer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, provided it is super-insulated on the external fa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce, reduces heat demand in winter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. One </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">barrier to any use of inter-seasonal heat stores is that the benefits are not recognised by the Standard Assessment Procedure (SAP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which underpins building regulations and energy performance certificates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Depart</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment of Communities and Local Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> did not list this as an issue for the SAP Integrity Group to address in the latest review of this process</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also note that the health and comfort benefits of insulation measures cannot be delivered in the absenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of ventilation. We welcome the commitment by DECC to work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with experts and other government departments to understand the potential risk of overheating; provide guidance on homes which are most likely to be vulnerable to overheating and what steps could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be taken to minimise the risk; and to ensure that best practice is implemented throughout the energy efficiency supply chain. It is essential that these steps are taken to ensure that concerns around overheating do not negatively impact on the much more si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gnificant challenge of insulating our housing stock. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The research on why this may be the case is limited, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we suggest that barriers to the take-up of heat pumps in a domestic setting will include: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of consumer familiarity with the technologies and their operation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">High up-front costs of installation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disruption associated with installation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Higher than expec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted running costs, particularly where properties are poorly insulated</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reported poor experiences, perhaps related to some of the above</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consumer Futures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is technology neutral and there are clearly some issues to be addressed in the application of heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to domestic properties, however we have identified ways to promote new heating technologies from our work across technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Measures to promote new heating technologies</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">asy to use controls and support for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to understand how to use their new systems on an ongoing basis; lack of such support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in recent research by Consumer Focus Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was associated with confusion, inefficient use of the systems, and therefore higher costs.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greater visibility of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> renewab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le heat technologies in buildings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h high public footfalls, together with promotional materials explaining how the systems work and associated cost and carbon savings would help. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We strongly advocate a central ‘online calculator’, backed by the Governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent, that could assist consumers in working out whether the RHI will be beneficial for their home. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such a calculator would need to be accompanied by a number of caveats to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">protect against possible misselling, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consumers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need assistance with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">what is a ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ry complex decision and those caveats could form the basis of a checklist that should be completed by potential providers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government should make sure that current and forthcoming initiatives, including the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI), the Green De</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al and the ECO, are structured to provide an integrated package of s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">upport for off-grid consumers. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.  What is government policy doing to pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thermal storage is useful, but</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is likely to cause confusion for consumers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Space for storage in the home is decreasing</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government’s energy performance procedure does not recognise the value of intersea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sonal thermal storage</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> into time of use tariffs</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shows that consumers are often confused by metering arrangements, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have difficulties understanding bills, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do not understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> unit prices for electric heating, even at off-peak times, remain more expensive than mains gas. In addition, some consumers require assistance to understand how to use their existing heating systems efficiently.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These problems arise in relation to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most tried-and-tested form of storage in Britain’s homes, the electric storage heater, and so we are concerned about such problems occurring with other storage technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omestic thermal storage is currently decreasing with the roll-out of combi-boile</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs. Currently there is little incentive for consumers to have thermal storage in their homes, and these trends mean it may be increasingly difficult to find space for storage in future if required. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is likely that thermal storage will be more appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where there is the ability to develop a community-scale facility, either for new-build homes or in retrofitted community heat schemes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:105%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regarding inter-seasonal balancing, the Government should explore the use of high thermal mass and passive solar gain t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o store heat. As outlined earlier, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high levels of thermal mass have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the added benefit of keeping buildings cool in summer. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> main barrier to any use of inter-seasonal heat stores is that the benefits are not recognised by the Standard Assessment Procedur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be addressed through the Procedure’s review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Consumer Focus, 2013, Submission to the Energy and Climate Change Committee, Green Deal watching brief, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmenergy/142/142we10.htm</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:107%; margin:6pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">UK-GBC Task Group Report: Retrofit Incentives, http://www.ukgbc.org/resources/publication/uk-gbc-task-group-report-retrofit-incentives</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Consumer Futures is currently carrying </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">out a research project looking at how such an initiative could work.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:107%; margin:6pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Consumer Focus/William Baker, 2011, Off-gas consumers: Information on households without mains gas heating, </span><a href="http://www.consumerfocus.org.uk/publications/off-gas-consumers-information-on-households-without-mains-gas-heating"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.consumerfocus.org.uk/publications/off-gas-consumers-information-on-households-without-mains-gas-heating</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Consumer Futures, 2013, the Hardest Hit, </span><a href="http://www.consumerfutures.org.uk/reports/the-hardest-hit-going-beyond-the-mean-a-report-by-cse-on-the-impact-of-energy-policy-on-consumers-bills"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.consumerfutures.org.uk/reports/the-hardest-hit-going-beyond-the-mean-a-report-by-cse-on-the-impact-of-energy-policy-on-consumers-</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">bills</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Programme stats for previous Scottish energy efficiency programmes have been published here: http://www.energysavingtrust.org.uk/scotland/Publications2/Take-action/Home-Energy-Programmes-Detailed-Report-2009-2013-Excel</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.consumerfocus.org.uk/scotland/publications/keeping-the-heat-in-scotlands-homes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DECC (2012) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A consultation on proposed changes to the Government’s Standard Assessment Procedure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.bre.co.uk/sap2012/page.jsp?id=2759</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Consumer Futures (2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">012) From devotees to the disengaged – time of use tariffs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">http://www.consumerfutures.org.uk/reports/from-devotees-to-the-disengaged-time-of-use-tariffs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>